The best rainbows are not the big ones in the sky. They are the tiny ones I find in my garden after a summer shower.

I like the rainbow that appears in a puddle near the old oak tree. When the sun peeks out from behind the grey clouds, the water sparkles. It looks like a little bridge made of colours. Red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo and violet dance on the wet stones.

Sometimes, I see a rainbow in a bubble. My little sister blows them with her wand. They float up, catching the light. For a second, they are perfect circles of colour before they pop with a soft *plip*.

My favourite rainbow is the one in a glass of lemonade. When I hold it up to the window, the light shines through the yellow drink. It makes a bright, warm glow on the table. It tastes sweet and looks magical.

These small rainbows are special because I can touch them or drink them. They remind me that even on a rainy day in the UK, there is always a little bit of magic waiting to be found. [end of text]


